WEBVTT

p01
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.349
Start in CRM, open Customers, and click into the member's record.

p02
00:00:01.599 --> 00:00:04.346
Customer three-sixty opens on nine tabs,

p03
00:00:05.185 --> 00:00:10.035
with the header carrying Back, Delete, Edit Customer, and the green Actions menu.

p04
00:00:10.245 --> 00:00:12.931
That green menu decides most of this playbook.

p05
00:00:13.607 --> 00:00:17.669
Leave it closed for now.

p06
00:00:18.364 --> 00:00:20.880
First you confirm what the member actually holds.

p07
00:00:21.336 --> 00:00:22.781
Open the Membership tab.

p08
00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:26.128
Plan details gives you the membership type, the home location, and the status.

p09
00:00:26.459 --> 00:00:28.575
Billing cycle gives you the next charge.

p10
00:00:29.460 --> 00:00:31.712
Read status and next charge first.

p11
00:00:32.014 --> 00:00:34.430
A cancel or pause request only makes sense against an active plan,

p12
00:00:35.239 --> 00:00:44.515
and the next-charge date tells you how much time you have before the member gets billed again.

p13
00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:47.148
Now open the green Actions menu.

p14
00:00:47.406 --> 00:00:48.700
Look, don't touch.

p15
00:00:49.059 --> 00:00:51.159
It offers exactly two actions: Issue Wash and Refund Customer.

p16
00:00:51.423 --> 00:00:53.599
The legacy guide promised six, including cancel, pause, and reset.

p17
00:00:54.052 --> 00:00:58.501
Those are not here.

p18
00:00:58.790 --> 00:01:00.170
Whether they are role-gated or removed is an open question.

p19
00:01:00.511 --> 00:01:07.460
So never promise a member a change you cannot see a control for.

p20
00:01:07.751 --> 00:01:09.953
Close the menu without selecting anything.

p21
00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:12.646
Decide the branch before you navigate.

p22
00:01:13.310 --> 00:01:16.060
A refund is a live action, so it gets gated:

p23
00:01:16.467 --> 00:01:19.234
who can approve it, and which standard reason applies.

p24
00:01:19.848 --> 00:01:24.445
A cancel, pause, or reset is not a demo action, so it routes by role.

p25
00:01:24.947 --> 00:01:26.938
Either way, the interaction gets logged.

p26
00:01:27.263 --> 00:01:29.094
Two branches. One log.

p27
00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:31.150
Take the refund branch first.

p28
00:01:31.553 --> 00:01:32.252
Settings, Users and Security, Security Level.

p29
00:01:32.571 --> 00:01:34.909
Three columns: name, level, and refund approval required.

p30
00:01:35.445 --> 00:01:36.302
That last column is the gate.

p31
00:01:36.610 --> 00:01:37.104
It marks, per level, whether a refund needs sign-off before anyone can process it.

p32
00:01:37.435 --> 00:01:39.878
Today's capture returned a fetch error in place of rows,

p33
00:01:40.413 --> 00:01:54.160
so confirm the list loaded before you read a level's answer.

p34
00:01:54.626 --> 00:01:57.440
Read the approval column against the requester's level.

p35
00:01:57.964 --> 00:01:59.126
Per the verified walk, Low, Low Medium, and Medium all require approval.

p36
00:01:59.425 --> 00:02:03.038
So a Low or Medium user hands the refund to a High Medium or High approver

p37
00:02:03.469 --> 00:02:10.172
instead of processing it themselves.

p38
00:02:10.869 --> 00:02:14.236
Confirm the live yes or no per level at ticket time.

p39
00:02:14.595 --> 00:02:16.560
The mapping was not observable today.

p40
00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:18.118
Next, the reason. Settings, Operations, Refund Reasons.

p41
00:02:18.579 --> 00:02:21.330
One description column, one job:

p42
00:02:21.827 --> 00:02:23.703
every refund gets tagged with a standard reason so reporting stays clean.

p43
00:02:24.041 --> 00:02:27.986
Pick from this list, never freehand.

p44
00:02:28.337 --> 00:02:30.606
The rows did not load in today's capture,

p45
00:02:31.374 --> 00:02:36.073
so the live list is your source at ticket time.

p46
00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:37.708
Now the other branch.

p47
00:02:39.465 --> 00:02:44.716
Cancel, pause, and reset are not in the demo menu, and that cuts both ways.

p48
00:02:45.074 --> 00:02:49.609
You do not promise the change, and you do not tell the member it cannot be done.

p49
00:02:50.387 --> 00:02:53.064
On production, confirm your role can perform it.

p50
00:02:53.500 --> 00:02:56.256
If it cannot, route the request to someone who can.

p51
00:02:56.844 --> 00:02:58.473
That is the whole move.

p52
00:02:58.948 --> 00:03:00.265
Whatever happened, log it.

p53
00:03:00.265 --> 00:03:02.597
Back on Customer three-sixty, open Notes.

p54
00:03:02.597 --> 00:03:06.229
These are internal staff notes, not visible to the customer,

p55
00:03:06.229 --> 00:03:09.522
with pin and save controls, and the communication history below.

p56
00:03:09.522 --> 00:03:14.050
Record what the member asked, what you did or routed, and any approval.

p57
00:03:14.050 --> 00:03:16.597
Pin it if the account is critical.

p58
00:03:16.597 --> 00:03:18.814
And never log it in Messaging.

p59
00:03:18.814 --> 00:03:20.461
That tab texts the customer.

p60
00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:21.852
Then package it.

p61
00:03:21.852 --> 00:03:23.730
The member.

p62
00:03:23.730 --> 00:03:25.674
The exact change they asked for.

p63
00:03:25.674 --> 00:03:28.832
The refund reason if one applies.

p64
00:03:28.832 --> 00:03:33.072
The requester's security level and whether approval is required.

p65
00:03:33.072 --> 00:03:36.113
And who it routes to.

p66
00:03:36.113 --> 00:03:38.610
You verified and you logged.

p67
00:03:38.610 --> 00:03:42.170
The cancel, the pause, the refund itself,

p68
00:03:42.170 --> 00:03:45.808
all of that happens in production with the right role.

p69
00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:47.341
That's the playbook.

p70
00:03:48.183 --> 00:03:49.830
Confirm the plan on Membership.

p71
00:03:50.407 --> 00:03:54.064
Read the Actions menu for what the platform will actually let you do.

p72
00:03:54.744 --> 00:03:58.885
Gate a refund through Security Levels and tag it from Refund Reasons.

p73
00:03:59.781 --> 00:04:01.984
Route a cancel or pause by role.

p74
00:04:02.739 --> 00:04:05.560
And log everything in Notes, never Messaging.

p75
00:04:06.166 --> 00:04:07.918
Every screen stayed read-only.

